          "body": "Verses 17-18 are the theological core of the psalm. David does not base his cry for help on his own righteousness — he bases it on his own transparency. 'I am ready to fall, and my sorrow is continually before me. For I confess my iniquity; I am full of anxiety because of my sin' (38:17-18). The Hebrew verb *nagad* (I confess, declare, make known) places his iniquity openly in God's sight, paralleling verse 9 where all his desire and sighing were placed before God. This is the penitential structure of the whole psalm: the body's devastation (38:1-10), the community's abandonment (38:11-16), and the conscience's anxiety (38:17-18) are all disclosed to God, none of them explained away. It is precisely because David does not hide his sin that he can cry urgently for help. The contrast with the enemies in 38:19-20 sharpens the point: their vigorous strength, their wrongful hatred, their repaying evil for good — these stand over against David's self-confessed moral failure. The irony is deliberate: the man who admits he has sinned is the man God will vindicate; the men who repay good with evil are the ones who have no ground to stand on. Keller observes that true prayer does not bring a cleaned-up version of yourself to God — it brings the real version, iniquities and all, counting on the God who is faithful and righteous to receive it."
