          "body": "The psalm closes with two verses that compress all three divine names from across the psalm into a single appeal: YHWH (38:21), Elohim (38:21, 22), and Adonai (38:22). The structure is chiastic: 'Do not forsake me, O LORD / O my God, do not be far from me / Make haste to help me / O Lord, my salvation' (38:21-22). The opening plea ('do not forsake me') echoes the verb *azav* already used in verse 10 where David's own strength had abandoned him — now he begs that God will not imitate his failing body. The closing title — 'my salvation' (*yeshuah*) — is the psalm's final word and its loudest one. After twenty-two verses of arrows, festering wounds, groaning, isolation, and enemy scheming, David's last word for God is 'my Savior.' The trajectory is complete: the God whose discipline opened the psalm in anger (38:1) is the same God whose salvation closes it in hope (38:22). The psalm is not resolved by circumstances changing but by the confidence that the God who sees all desire and sighing (38:9) will answer (38:15) and will not be far (38:21). As the superscription suggested, David has brought his whole condition as a memorial before God — and that act of offering is itself the foundation of his hope."
