        "number": 2,
        "title": "The abandoned man — isolation, silence, and the redirection of speech",
        "range": "38:11-16",
        "excerpt": "My loved ones and my friends stand aloof from my plague; and my kinsmen stand afar off.",
        "body": "The movement from physical devastation (38:1-10) to relational abandonment (38:11-16) is not a change of subject — it is the same catastrophe widening. Sin's consequences do not stay interior. The *nega* of verse 11 — most commonly translated 'plague' in the NASB, but the standard Hebrew term for the skin disease of Leviticus 13-14 — carries its full social weight. In the Torah, the person afflicted with *nega* was isolated from the community, required to call out 'Unclean! Unclean!' (Leviticus 13:45-46), and excluded from normal human contact. Whether David's condition is literally leprous or metaphorically so, the social effect is identical: those who should stand nearest stand farthest away.\n\nThe enemies of verse 12 function as the dark foil to the distanced friends. Friends are passively absent; enemies are actively hostile. The verbs accumulate: lay snares, threaten destruction, devise treachery — and this 'all day long,' matching the 'all day long' mourning of verse 6. The two *kol hayom* (all day long) phrases bracket David's existence: unrelieved mourning within, unrelenting hostility without. This is total siege.\n\nDavid's response to the siege is counterintuitive: he becomes deaf and mute (38:13-14). He 'does not hear' the enemy's accusations; his mouth has 'no arguments' in response. This is not the silence of a broken man — it is the silence of a man who has decided where to speak. Verse 15 discloses the reasoning: 'For I hope in You, O LORD.' The connective *ki* (for, because) reveals that the silence before men is the direct consequence of the hope directed toward God. To defend yourself before your accusers is to make them the relevant tribunal. David has relocated the courtroom. He will answer only before the Judge who matters.\n\nThis posture has a striking New Testament counterpart. Before Pilate and the chief priests, Jesus 'gave him no answer, not even to a single charge, so that the governor was greatly amazed' (Matthew 27:14; cf. Isaiah 53:7 — 'He was oppressed and afflicted, yet He did not open His mouth'). The silence of the righteous sufferer before human accusers while maintaining speech before the Father is a pattern that runs from Psalm 38 through the Suffering Servant of Isaiah to the cross itself.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nega* (plague, v.11) — the technical term for the skin condition of Leviticus 13-14 that required social exclusion; its presence here evokes the Torah's isolation-protocol. *Yachal* (hope, v.15) — to wait with confident expectation, the posture of sustained trust rather than anxious demand. *Cheresh* and *illem* (deaf and mute, v.13) — two different conditions of communicative disability; together they describe total social withdrawal from the enemy's voice."
